            . On the 21st of June I had a warrant granted me against the prisoner, for taking a watch away, the property of 
               <persName id="t17640728-42-person395">
                  Thomas 
                  Flaharty 
               <interp inst="t17640728-42-person395" type="surname" value="Flaharty"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17640728-42-person395" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17640728-42-person395" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            ; he denied having any watch about him, both before and at Justice Welch's: Mr. Welch ordered me to search him, and I found this watch under his armpit (producing a silver watch); the man that lost the watch is now in Newgate, for receiving<xptr type="pageFacsimile" doc="176407280024"></xptr> stolen goods, and cast for transportation for fourteen years.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t17640728-42-person396">
                  Thomas 
                  Windsor 
               <interp inst="t17640728-42-person396" type="surname" value="Windsor"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17640728-42-person396" type="given" value="Thomas"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t17640728-42-person396" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
             Allen. This is Mr. Flaharty's property: in May 1763, I cleaned and mended it for him, and had four shillings for doing it: when he had lost it he came and told me of it; the constable had him in custody at the same time: this was about five weeks ago.</p>
               <p>Prisoner's Defence.</p>
               <p>I had the watch, the night before this gentleman lays he took me, of a seaman that came from Vortsmouth; I lent him a guinea upon it: after that, Flaharty came to my shop, and said I had robbed him of his watch.</p>
